# Jira Writing Standards

## Project Reference
- Project key: `WEL`
- Jira instance: `belias.atlassian.net`
- Fix Version IDs: `mvp`=10000 / `post-mvp`=10001 / `deferred`=10002

---

## Required Fields — Every Item

No item may be written to Jira without all of the following fields populated:

| Field | Jira mechanism | Required value |
|---|---|---|
| Summary | `summary` | Clear, specific title. No vague names like "Fix bug" or "New feature". |
| Issue type | `issue_type` | `Feature` / `Story` / `Task` / `Bug` / `Spike` |
| Layer | Label | Exactly one `layer:*` label |
| Component | Label | Exactly one `component:*` label |
| Impact radius | Label | Exactly one `impact:*` label |
| Re-eval flag | Label | Exactly one `re-eval:*` label (default: `re-eval:clean`) |
| Triage session | Label | `triage-YYYY-MM-DD-NNN` for the current session |
| Phase | Fix Version | `mvp`, `post-mvp`, or `deferred` |
| Priority | Priority field | `P0-blocker`, `P1-critical`, `P2-important`, or `P3-backlog` |
| Description | `description` | At minimum: one sentence describing the work and its purpose. Stories and Features must reference the relevant `docs/` section. |

---

## Triage Session ID Format

Format: `triage-YYYY-MM-DD-NNN`

- `YYYY-MM-DD` is the date the triage run starts
- `NNN` is a zero-padded sequence number starting at `001`, incremented per triage run per day
- Example: `triage-2026-05-30-001`, `triage-2026-05-30-002`

The session ID is a label applied to every item created or updated in that run. It must be consistent across all items in a single triage run.

---

## Issue Link Types

Only three link types are used. No others.

| Link type | When to use |
|---|---|
| `blocks` | This item must be completed before the linked item can start |
| `is blocked by` | This item cannot start until the linked item is complete |
| `relates to` | Architectural or conceptual relationship — no hard sequencing dependency |

Every Feature must have at least one link to another Feature (`blocks`, `is blocked by`, or `relates to`). Isolated Features are not allowed — they are a signal that the component relationship is missing.

---

## Deferred Gap Format

When VERIFY finds a gap and the user defers it, create the following item:

- Issue type: `Story`
- Summary: `[Deferred] <description of the gap>`
- Fix Version: `deferred`
- Priority: `P3-backlog`
- Label: `re-eval:needs-review`
- Label: `triage-YYYY-MM-DD-NNN` (current session)
- Label: `layer:*` and `component:*` of the gap area
- Description: "Deferred during triage session `triage-YYYY-MM-DD-NNN`. Gap: <what was missing and why it was deferred>."

Nothing discovered during a triage run is allowed to disappear. If it's not handled now, it becomes a deferred item.

---

## Description Standards

**Features:** Must include: (1) one-sentence purpose statement, (2) link to the relevant `docs/system-design/` or `docs/feature-backlog/` section, (3) which components it depends on.

**Stories:** Must include: (1) user-facing or system outcome, (2) acceptance criteria as a bullet list, (3) which Feature it belongs to.

**Tasks:** Must include: (1) specific technical action, (2) definition of done.

**Bugs:** Must include: (1) observed behavior, (2) expected behavior, (3) steps to reproduce if known.

**Spikes:** Must include: (1) the question being investigated, (2) time-box, (3) expected output (decision, doc, or prototype).
